habitat_description:
The Pale Lumped-nosed Bat roosts predominantly in gypsum caves but also uses mines, rock crevices, and some human structures (Smith et al. 2008).  It’s distribution is not determined by vegetation associations.  Usually only found in broken, rocky terrain, it has been found in communities ranging from desert scrub to pinyon-juniper woodlands (Ammerman et al. 2012).  They stay relatively active during winter (Ammerman et al. 2012). N. Tarr, 3/7/2014. 
 
Also see Townsend’s Big-eared Bat habitat description.
